{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3307189,"name":"Krishna Shah","username":"DragonflyRobotics","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/d/a6a055/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-02-11T20:05:24.329Z","cooked":"<p>Hello,</p>
<p>We just finished our first swerve drive train and everything runs fine. We wrote custom kinematics that handles module position so there is an external <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> handling our angle motors. All of our SparkMax and Neos are flashed to factory default. Is there any point in <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> tuning the SparkMax with the corresponding Neo (perhaps for better drive velocity)? If so, how would one go about this?</p>
<p>Clarification:<br>
Our team has never conventionally tuned the internal <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> loop of the Neo that uses the internal hall effect encoder to adjust velocity and speed. Is this necessary for best accuracy during autonomous and drive? Furthermore, how  would you tune (get the error graph) that internal <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> loop (I know the gains are accessible via REV hardware client)?</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":10,"updated_at":"2024-02-11T20:58:24.544Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":144,"reads":115,"readers_count":114,"score":743.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":454364,"topic_slug":"tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train","display_username":"Krishna Shah","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":3,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":61948,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train/454364/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3307193,"name":"Skye Leake","username":"Skyehawk","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/skyehawk/{size}/179363_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-11T20:13:10.736Z","cooked":"<p>Could you update the title (if you can) with a few more details so it is easier for people with experience to notice and click into the thread?  “<span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> tune for neo…”  is pretty generic. Perhaps something along the lines of : “Tuning of swerve spark maxes with external PIDs controlling position.” ?</p>
<p>I have to admit I am not quite grasping the scope of what you are asking so more clarification in the title and thread would be useful to me at least. Perhaps breaking the problem down into smaller pieces. Just to help us get you help efficiently.</p>
<p><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/images/emoji/google/slight_smile.png?v=12" title=":slight_smile:" class="emoji only-emoji" alt=":slight_smile:" loading="lazy" width="20" height="20"></p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":10,"updated_at":"2024-02-11T20:15:23.056Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":107,"readers_count":106,"score":36.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":454364,"topic_slug":"tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train","display_username":"Skye Leake","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":true,"admin":false,"staff":true,"user_id":19235,"hidden":false,"trust_level":4,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Pretengineer"},"post_url":"/t/tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train/454364/2","custom_user_title":"Pretengineer","reactions":[{"id":"point_up","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3307223,"name":"Krishna Shah","username":"DragonflyRobotics","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/d/a6a055/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-02-11T20:58:50.777Z","cooked":"<p>Thanks for your response! I have clarified my question and title, I hope that helps!</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":10,"updated_at":"2024-02-11T20:58:50.777Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":81,"readers_count":80,"score":21.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":454364,"topic_slug":"tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train","display_username":"Krishna Shah","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":19235,"username":"Skyehawk","name":"Skye Leake","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/skyehawk/{size}/179363_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":61948,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train/454364/3","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3307224,"name":"","username":"Wesley","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/wesley/{size}/155134_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-11T20:58:54.536Z","cooked":"<p>I think what you’re asking is: Is it useful to set up <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> control on the SparkMAX if there’s a separate control loop running on the rio?</p>
<p>If so, then mostly no.  If you have a PIDController on the robot for module azimuth, then you don’t want to use the SparkMAX <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> for the angle motor— you’ll treat it like a “dumb” motor controller, only calling ‘set()’.</p>
<p>However, you may want to reconsider using a rio-based pid if possible— the SparkMAX control loop runs at 1kHz, while the rio only runs at 50Hz.</p>
<p>Additionally, you certainly can still use the velocity control loop on the <em>drive</em> motor, if you need closed-loop velocity control at all.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":10,"updated_at":"2024-02-11T20:58:54.536Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":79,"readers_count":78,"score":30.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":454364,"topic_slug":"tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":48578,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"95's programming team from 2021 to 2024"},"post_url":"/t/tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train/454364/4","custom_user_title":"95's programming team from 2021 to 2024","reactions":[{"id":"+1","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3307227,"name":"Krishna Shah","username":"DragonflyRobotics","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/d/a6a055/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-02-11T21:00:39.057Z","cooked":"<p>Doesn’t .set() use the <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> loop in the SparkMax? I guess you can make the P=1, D=0, and I=0 to make it a “dumb motor”. If I wanted to tune the drive motor, where can I find the error graph for the target and actual velocity/position?</p>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":10,"updated_at":"2024-02-11T21:00:39.057Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":4,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":76,"readers_count":75,"score":20.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":454364,"topic_slug":"tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train","display_username":"Krishna Shah","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":48578,"username":"Wesley","name":"","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/wesley/{size}/155134_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":61948,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train/454364/5","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3307230,"name":"","username":"Wesley","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/wesley/{size}/155134_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-11T21:05:31.183Z","cooked":"<p>.set(speed) is a method of the CANSparkMax object, and tells the motor to run at (speed * 100) percent of full speed.</p>
<p>Once you get the pid controller object using .getPIDController(), you can use the .setRefrence() method on the pid controller object to set a controller setpoint.</p>","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"posts_count":10,"updated_at":"2024-02-11T21:05:31.183Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":5,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":73,"readers_count":72,"score":19.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":454364,"topic_slug":"tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":61948,"username":"DragonflyRobotics","name":"Krishna Shah","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/d/a6a055/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":48578,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"95's programming team from 2021 to 2024"},"post_url":"/t/tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train/454364/6","custom_user_title":"95's programming team from 2021 to 2024","reactions":[{"id":"+1","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3307234,"name":"viggy96","username":"viggy96","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/viggy96/{size}/252784_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-11T21:10:37.705Z","cooked":"<p>Controlling velocity accurately can provide an additional level of accuracy during autonomous. While its not technically necessary, as far as I’ve seen most swerve frameworks/examples do use velocity <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> control on the drive motor.</p>
<p>What swerve module are you using?</p>
<p>You can usually copy someone else’s <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> variables who is using the same swerve module as you.</p>
<p>We’re using MAXSwerve modules, and I know for the drive velocity <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> the values should be:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">private static final double DRIVE_VELOCITY_kP = 0.04;
...
 m_driveConversionFactor = DRIVE_WHEEL_DIAMETER_METERS * Math.PI / m_driveGearRatio.value;
    m_driveMotor.setPositionConversionFactor(Spark.FeedbackSensor.NEO_ENCODER, m_driveConversionFactor);
    m_driveMotor.setVelocityConversionFactor(Spark.FeedbackSensor.NEO_ENCODER, m_driveConversionFactor / 60);
...
new PIDConstants(
  DRIVE_VELOCITY_kP,
  0.0,
  0.0,
  1 / ((m_driveMotor.getKind().getMaxRPM() / 60) * m_driveConversionFactor)
)
</code></pre>
<p>This is pulled from PurpleLib, the library that our team has developed, and has MAXSwerve support built-in. You can do all this manually though even without our library.</p>","post_number":7,"post_type":1,"posts_count":10,"updated_at":"2024-02-11T21:13:17.862Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":7,"reads":72,"readers_count":71,"score":84.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":454364,"topic_slug":"tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train","display_username":"viggy96","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":2}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":24613,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"418 Mentor | Tries to be smart"},"post_url":"/t/tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train/454364/7","custom_user_title":"418 Mentor | Tries to be smart","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":2}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":2,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3307255,"name":"Krishna Shah","username":"DragonflyRobotics","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/d/a6a055/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-02-11T21:32:19.602Z","cooked":"<p>This is quite helpful since we wrote our custom drivebase framework. How can I quickly tune it by getting the error value?</p>","post_number":8,"post_type":1,"posts_count":10,"updated_at":"2024-02-11T21:32:56.710Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":7,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":3,"reads":61,"readers_count":60,"score":32.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":454364,"topic_slug":"tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train","display_username":"Krishna Shah","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":24613,"username":"viggy96","name":"viggy96","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/viggy96/{size}/252784_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":61948,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/tune-internal-pid-loop-for-drive-angle-motor-swerve-drive-train/454364/8","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3307261,"name":"viggy96","username":"viggy96","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/viggy96/{size}/252784_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-11T21:44:05.672Z","cooked":"<p>You could log outputs using AdvantageKit, as I’ve always had issues with the REV Hardware Client graph not working.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">Logger.logOutputs("DriveSubsystem/DesiredSwerveState", m_desiredStates);
Logger.logOutputs("DriveSubsystem/ActualSwerveState", getCurrentStates());
</code></pre>
<p>And you can browse to those in AdvantageScope, and graph the velocity.</p>
<p>However, I can tell you that if you’re using a NEO or Vortex for drive, the above values should work for you, if you’re using MAXSwerve or <span class="abbreviation">SDS<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Swerve Drive Specialties"></template></span> MK4 modules.<br>
Team 5406 Celt-X has forked PurpleLib and has been developing <span class="abbreviation">SDS<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Swerve Drive Specialties"></template></span> MK4 module support, and are using the same values above.</p>
